MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Patch 0048's hand-rolled fast path calls SDL_FlushRenderer(_renderer)
before each direct write to ensure prior queued slow-path drawcalls
land in window->surface before our fast-path overlay. This is required
for z-order correctness when slow-path and fast-path drawcalls
interleave.

But on title scene cirrus7 fastpath audit reports ~98.9% of drawcalls
take the fast path. So the renderer queue is almost always already
empty when fast path calls FlushRenderer. SDL_FlushRenderer's
empty-queue early-return at SDL_render.c §343 is cheap, but it's
still a function-call + parameter validation pass per drawcall ×
340/frame.

Fix: track a per-renderer "queue dirty" bit. Set in every slow-path
render call site (RenderTexture / RenderTextureRotated / RenderLine /
RenderFillRect / RenderFillRects). Read in fast-path: skip the flush
when clean. Cleared after flush, and after SDL_RenderPresent in flip()
and flushAll() since RenderPresent implicitly flushes.

Slow-path call sites instrumented with `_renderer_queue_dirty = true`:
  * Renderer::drawSurface         (SDL_RenderTexture via timed helper)
  * Renderer::drawSurfaceMirrored (SDL_RenderTextureRotated via timed helper)
  * Renderer::blitPatternAcross   (SDL_RenderTexture)
  * Renderer::drawLine            (SDL_RenderLine)
  * Renderer::drawRect            (SDL_RenderFillRects)
  * Renderer::fillRect            (SDL_RenderFillRect)
  * Renderer::tintScreen          (SDL_RenderFillRect)
  * Renderer::clearScreen         (SDL_RenderFillRect)
  * Renderer::drawSpotLight       (SDL_RenderTexture)

Cleared in:
  * Renderer::flip       (after SDL_RenderPresent)
  * Renderer::flushAll   (after SDL_RenderPresent)
  * _try_fast_blit_16x16 (after the conditional SDL_FlushRenderer)

First slow-path → fast-path transition behavior: slow path sets
dirty=true, fast path on next call sees dirty, performs SDL_Flush-
Renderer (which empties the queue and lands the slow-path output on
window->surface), clears dirty=false, then performs its direct write.
Z-order is preserved exactly as in the unconditional-flush version.

Reverse case (fast-path → slow-path): patch 0048's analysis still
applies — the slow-path queues a command and the fast-path's prior
direct write is already on window->surface, so when SDL_RenderPresent
or the next fast-path's flush drains the queue, the slow-path output
composites on top of the fast-path output exactly as if both went
through the renderer.

Smoke-tested under DOSBox-X parity (build/stage runs cleanly, title
renders correctly, intro scene proceeds, character moves).
fastpath audit shows the same ~415/2370 ratio as wave 7, so the
gating logic is unchanged — only the cost-per-fastpath-call is
reduced.

Expected real-HW saving: ~340 × N µs per frame where N is the per-
SDL_FlushRenderer-empty-queue cost on real HW. Combined with patch
0050's GetWindowSurface-cache, the per-call overhead in the fast
path drops by both contributors.

